Lab 2 Report: Advanced UI Implementation
Project Description
This lab involved the development of an Advanced Enrollment Dashboard using a CSS Grid architecture. The primary focus was on implementing a responsive, mobile-first administrative interface capable of handling manual user registration and bulk data processing via CSV.
Requirements Checklist1. CSS Grid & Responsive Layout
The dashboard utilizes a mobile-first approach to ensure cross-device compatibility.

* Mobile View: The .dashboard-container is structured as a single-column stack by default.
* Desktop View: A media query for screens wider than 1024px (iPad Pro) switches the layout to a two-column grid, featuring a 350px sidebar for the Enrollment Portal and a flexible area for the Active Directory table.

2. Registration & Business Logic
The system follows a specific hierarchy for user management:

* Role Assignment: The first registered user is automatically assigned Admin status, while all subsequent registrations are classified as Employees.
* Data Requirements: Registration requires an Email and Password, with a Name field provided as an optional input.
* Workflow Constraints: The system requires all prior attendance to be uploaded before an employee's schedule can be updated.

3. File Upload Specifications
Two distinct CSV formats are supported for bulk operations:

* Schedule Upload: Uses a three-column format (Email, Start Time, End Time) with times in 24-hour format (hh:mm:ss).
* Attendance Upload: Handles complex data strings including Start Date, Time-In, End Date, Time-Out, Break, and Total Work durations.

4. Accessibility Audit
Evaluation via Chrome Lighthouse ensured high-performance standards:

* Contrast: High-contrast color palettes (light background/dark text) are used to meet AA accessibility standards.
* ARIA Landmarks: Semantic HTML5 landmarks (<main>, <section>) and ARIA roles like role="main" and aria-labelledby provide a clear navigational structure for screen readers.

5. Keyboard Navigation
Full system operability is maintained through keyboard-only interactions:

* All interactive elements, including form inputs and action buttons, are reachable via the Tab key.
* A distinct blue outline is applied to the :focus state in the CSS to provide clear visual feedback for keyboard users.

6. Device Simulation

* iPhone SE: Confirmed that components stack vertically and the table remains usable via its responsive wrapper.
* iPad Pro: Confirmed the grid successfully expands into the full desktop layout.
